Interview Questions

Q1. What is a Vector in Java?
-->Vector is a legacy class in the Java Collections Framework that implements the List interface. It is similar to ArrayList but is synchronized, making it thread-safe. It maintains insertion order, allows duplicate elements, and permits null values.

Example:

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>();

        vector.add("Java");
        vector.add("Python");

        System.out.println(vector);
    }
}




Q2. How does Vector work internally?
-->Vector internally uses a dynamic array (Object[]) to store elements.

      When the array becomes full, it automatically increases its capacity.
      By default, the capacity doubles when more space is needed (unless a custom capacity increment is specified).
      
      Example:
      
      Capacity = 10
      
      After full →
      
      New Capacity = 20
      
      It supports random access because elements are stored in contiguous memory.



Q3. Why is Vector considered a legacy class?
-->Vector is considered a legacy class because:

      It was introduced in Java 1.0, before the Collections Framework.
      It was later integrated into the Collections Framework in Java 1.2.
      It is synchronized by default, which reduces performance in single-threaded applications.
      ArrayList is generally preferred because it is faster when thread safety is not required.




Q4. Is Vector synchronized or not?
-->Yes.

Vector is synchronized, which makes it thread-safe.

Every public method is synchronized, allowing multiple threads to use it safely. However, synchronization adds overhead,
 making Vector slower than ArrayList in single-threaded environments.



Q5. What is the initial capacity and default capacity of a Vector?
-->
| Type             | Capacity                 |
| ---------------- | ------------------------ |
| Initial Capacity | 10 (default constructor) |
| Default Capacity | 10                       |

When the capacity is exhausted, it typically doubles (unless a custom capacity increment is specified).




Q6. Can you store null values in a Vector?
-->Yes.
      
      Vector allows null values and duplicate elements.
      
      Example:
      
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>();
      
              vector.add(null);
              vector.add("Java");
              vector.add(null);
      
              System.out.println(vector);
          }
      }
      
      Output:
      
      [null, Java, null]
      
      

Q7. How many constructors are present in Vector?
-->Vector provides four constructors.

      1. Default Constructor
            Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>();
            
            Creates a Vector with an initial capacity of 10.
      
      2. Constructor with Initial Capacity
            Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>(20);
            
            Creates a Vector with an initial capacity of 20.
      
      3. Constructor with Initial Capacity and Capacity Increment
            Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>(10, 5);
            Initial capacity = 10
            Capacity increment = 5
      4. Constructor with Collection
            List<String> list = List.of("Java", "Python");
            
            Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>(list);
            
            Creates a Vector containing all elements from the specified collection.
      
      Interview Tip
            ArrayList → Faster, not synchronized, best for single-threaded applications.
            LinkedList → Best for frequent insertions and deletions.
            Vector → Synchronized, thread-safe, but slower due to synchronization overhead.

